WEBVTT

1
00:01:29.299 --> 00:01:34.179
THERE IS ONE KIDNAPPING EVERY 60 MINUTES
IN LATIN AMERICA.

2
00:01:34.262 --> 00:01:38.349
70% OF THE VICTIMS DO NOT SURVIVE.

3
00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:34.155
Family is everything, no?

4
00:02:34.239 --> 00:02:37.534
Now, do you love your son?

5
00:02:49.087 --> 00:02:52.715
Now, do you understand?

6
00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:58.221
You have a $10 million insurance policy.
I know that.

7
00:02:58.763 --> 00:03:00.223
Follow these instructions

8
00:03:00.473 --> 00:03:02.976
or God be with your child.

9
00:03:03.476 --> 00:03:04.853
You will remove your shirt

10
00:03:04.936 --> 00:03:07.063
and hold it out the window
to ID the car.

11
00:03:08.022 --> 00:03:10.024
Be professional.

12
00:03:11.109 --> 00:03:12.026
Come alone.

13
00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:08.708
EL PASO, TEXAS
USA-MEXICO BORDER

14
00:05:07.725 --> 00:05:13.231
Georgina! Obey me.
I will love you. Come on.

15
00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:16.526
- That's how it works, huh?
- That's right.

16
00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:26.911
She got a sister?

17
00:05:27.829 --> 00:05:29.914
How's business?

18
00:05:31.165 --> 00:05:34.127
The Japanese are here in a big way.

19
00:05:35.169 --> 00:05:42.135
Cheap labour, factory space, but they feel
a lot safer living over the border in El Paso.

20
00:05:42.218 --> 00:05:47.306
I ferry them back and forth.
They think I'm John Wayne.

21
00:05:51.728 --> 00:05:55.023
- I live like a king down here.
- Yes, you do.

22
00:05:58.568 --> 00:06:01.863
- You been workin'?
- Yeah. No.

23
00:06:01.946 --> 00:06:06.617
No. I've been movin' around. You know.
Colombia, a couple of places I can't name.

24
00:06:06.701 --> 00:06:09.996
Nothin' catches my fancy.

25
00:06:13.124 --> 00:06:16.627
You think God'll forgive us
for what we've done?

26
00:06:16.711 --> 00:06:18.921
- No.
- You don't?

27
00:06:19.005 --> 00:06:20.339
Me either.

28
00:06:22.592 --> 00:06:27.555
- How long you stayin'?
- I don't know, I just... you know.

29
00:06:27.638 --> 00:06:31.642
I wanted to see you, Ray,
see how you're doin'.

30
00:06:31.726 --> 00:06:34.312
I just came by on impulse.

31
00:06:34.395 --> 00:06:36.939
I could do with some impulse.

32
00:06:47.825 --> 00:06:49.911
What happened?

33
00:06:51.079 --> 00:06:57.502
Family paid the ransom, then they
sent the kid home after a couple of days.

34
00:06:57.585 --> 00:06:59.754
Minus an ear, of course.

35
00:06:59.837 --> 00:07:03.549
Now every mother in Mexico City
with money wants bigger bodyguards.

36
00:07:03.633 --> 00:07:07.929
- My own wife included.
- I hate to break it to you, but she's right.

37
00:07:08.012 --> 00:07:10.431
She's right.

38
00:07:10.515 --> 00:07:14.936
Look, Sammy, all my clients
have kidnap and ransom insurance.

39
00:07:15.019 --> 00:07:18.272
I have a policy.
AIG. My dad gave it to me.

40
00:07:18.356 --> 00:07:21.234
Yeah, I know. I got it for your dad.

41
00:07:21.317 --> 00:07:25.988
But what'll you do in 60 days when you can't
renew it because you have no bodyguard?

42
00:07:26.072 --> 00:07:28.950
I know. I had to let Emilio go.

43
00:07:29.033 --> 00:07:34.163
Well, you gotta please Lisa.
I mean, ass like that's hard to find.

44
00:07:35.206 --> 00:07:37.291
Look.

45
00:07:37.375 --> 00:07:42.713
A bodyguard's like anything else.
You get what you pay for, OK?

46
00:07:42.797 --> 00:07:45.758
You could do this.
Get one that's got a decent résumé.

47
00:07:45.842 --> 00:07:49.971
We're not lookin' for goddamn Superman,
right? Get someone cheap.

48
00:07:50.054 --> 00:07:56.686
So you renew the policy, and then
fire the prick for whatever - incompetence.

49
00:07:56.769 --> 00:08:01.440
All kidding aside, the most important thing
is that your daughter goes back to school,

50
00:08:01.524 --> 00:08:04.485
and that your wife gets to save face.

51
00:08:04.569 --> 00:08:11.075
This way you won't be the only
unprotected family in the neighbourhood.

52
00:08:21.335 --> 00:08:25.506
That's right, a bodyguard.
Your Spanish is good enough.

53
00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:28.676
- You're crazy.
- You even look the part.

54
00:08:28.759 --> 00:08:30.761
In my state, I couldn't guard a corpse.

55
00:08:30.845 --> 00:08:34.849
It's rich guys flashing their cash.
It's all for show. Nothing's gonna happen.

56
00:08:34.932 --> 00:08:39.437
Yeah? You think they'd
hire a drunk, a has-been?

57
00:08:40.813 --> 00:08:43.065
You have to keep it under control.

58
00:08:44.442 --> 00:08:49.280
What if there was, you know... just, say,
a kidnapping attempt? What do I do then?

59
00:08:49.363 --> 00:08:54.243
You do your best. They're not gonna be
paying you enough to perform miracles.

60
00:08:54.327 --> 00:08:58.748
It's not exactly a scam, Crease.
Even at half speed, you're pretty damn good.

61
00:08:58.831 --> 00:09:02.585
Yeah. A bodyguard's gotta
be close to people though.

62
00:09:02.668 --> 00:09:05.713
They talk all the time.
You know I'm no good at that.

63
00:09:05.796 --> 00:09:09.842
You'll be the silent type.
They're gonna appreciate that.

64
00:09:17.391 --> 00:09:19.685
Bodyguard. So who's the guy?

65
00:09:19.769 --> 00:09:22.563
Samuel Ramos. He's a young guy.

66
00:09:22.647 --> 00:09:26.943
- He owns one of the plants in Juárez.
- Yeah?

67
00:09:27.026 --> 00:09:29.487
The Jap car industry is in the toilet.

68
00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:32.990
He's trying to persuade Ford
to partner with him.

69
00:09:33.074 --> 00:09:36.911
I think he's in trouble.
His family lives in Mexico City.

70
00:09:36.994 --> 00:09:40.957
He asked me if I knew anybody he could trust.

71
00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:44.043
- And you thought of me?
- Yeah.

72
00:09:44.126 --> 00:09:47.672
Take a job, Crease. Breathe some air.

73
00:09:47.755 --> 00:09:50.007
Then decide if you want to stick around.

74
00:09:50.091 --> 00:09:54.387
Besides, I'm glad to see you, you know?
I got nobody to talk to down here.

75
00:10:01.978 --> 00:10:06.983
Listen, my wife wants
someone presentable and polite.

76
00:10:07.066 --> 00:10:10.611
You'll be the fifth candidate
she sees this week.

77
00:10:10.695 --> 00:10:12.446
Your résumé's quite impressive.

78
00:10:12.530 --> 00:10:17.076
16 years of military experience,
extensive counter-terrorism work.

79
00:10:17.159 --> 00:10:20.579
I'm surprised anybody could afford you.
What's the catch?

80
00:10:20.663 --> 00:10:22.873
I drink.

81
00:10:22.957 --> 00:10:25.042
How does that affect you?

82
00:10:27.628 --> 00:10:29.755
Coordination, reaction time.

83
00:10:29.839 --> 00:10:33.384
If top professionals try to kidnap
your daughter, I'll do the best I can,

84
00:10:33.467 --> 00:10:35.970
but the service will be on a par with the pay.

85
00:10:37.972 --> 00:10:39.974
What if amateurs try it?

86
00:10:40.057 --> 00:10:43.394
I'd probably kill 'em. Is that likely?

87
00:10:43.477 --> 00:10:45.354
No.

88
00:10:45.438 --> 00:10:50.693
No one is to know about your drinking.
That includes my wife.

89
00:11:16.010 --> 00:11:18.095
Lisa!

90
00:11:20.097 --> 00:11:22.183
Lisa!

91
00:11:34.111 --> 00:11:37.281
My wife Lisa.
And this is John Creasy.

92
00:11:43.245 --> 00:11:45.539
- You're an American.
- So are you.

93
00:11:46.916 --> 00:11:48.376
It's all in there.

94
00:11:53.339 --> 00:11:57.176
- Would you like a drink?
- Yes. Jack and water would be good.

95
00:11:58.511 --> 00:12:00.971
Have you done much of
this kind of work before?

96
00:12:01.055 --> 00:12:02.223
No, ma'am.

97
00:12:02.306 --> 00:12:06.143
But he has a lot of experience
in related fields.

98
00:12:08.521 --> 00:12:11.357
- Do you have a family, Mr Creasy?
- No.

99
00:12:11.899 --> 00:12:14.402
Pita? Pita.

100
00:12:18.197 --> 00:12:21.158
- Yes, Mom?
- Honey, this is Mr Creasy.

101
00:12:26.288 --> 00:12:31.293
It's English, honey. Do you wanna
show Mr Creasy to his room?

102
00:12:31.377 --> 00:12:33.838
- This way, Mr Creasy.
- OK.

103
00:12:43.556 --> 00:12:45.766
Thank you.

104
00:12:52.648 --> 00:12:54.024
Just like that?

105
00:12:55.484 --> 00:13:00.531
I think it's nice that he's an American.

106
00:13:00.614 --> 00:13:04.869
I think it's terrific. Are you sure?

107
00:13:07.496 --> 00:13:09.373
Thank you.

108
00:13:09.707 --> 00:13:11.333
Thank you.

109
00:13:12.376 --> 00:13:14.462
I feel better now.

110
00:13:19.800 --> 00:13:24.472
That's Bruno, the gardener.
And that's Maria, the cook.

111
00:13:29.643 --> 00:13:33.731
We fixed the room up two weeks ago.
It's nicer than before.

112
00:13:36.775 --> 00:13:40.738
You've got a TV and a CD player.
What kind of music do you like, Mr Creasy?

113
00:13:40.821 --> 00:13:44.492
- I don't know.
- You don't know?

114
00:13:44.575 --> 00:13:47.453
I don't know.

115
00:13:47.536 --> 00:13:52.124
That's Bird. Emilio forgot
to take him when he left.

116
00:13:53.167 --> 00:13:55.544
Emilio was my last bodyguard.

117
00:13:57.505 --> 00:14:01.759
Have you protected
a lot of children before, Mr Creasy?

118
00:14:01.842 --> 00:14:05.596
Creasy. You can call me Creasy.
And no, you're the first.

119
00:14:05.679 --> 00:14:07.515
Creasy.

120
00:14:07.598 --> 00:14:09.892
Bye, Creasy.

121
00:14:12.436 --> 00:14:14.313
Bye, Bird.

122
00:14:24.031 --> 00:14:29.078
- School tomorrow, Peeps.
- Does that mean we can get a dog?

123
00:14:29.161 --> 00:14:31.622
Dad promised me one
when I went back to school.

124
00:14:31.705 --> 00:14:33.874
Yeah, we'll see.

125
00:14:33.958 --> 00:14:38.963
If you get a dog, will you give up your bear?
You're getting too old for him.

126
00:14:41.799 --> 00:14:47.555
- How did you like Mr Creasy?
- Creasy. He said to call him just Creasy.

127
00:14:47.638 --> 00:14:51.684
- That isn't disrespectful, is it?
- No, not if he asked you.

128
00:14:51.767 --> 00:14:54.687
Here. There you go.

129
00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:04.613
He's like a bear too.

130
00:15:05.489 --> 00:15:07.700
- Yeah?
- A big, sad bear.

131
00:15:10.077 --> 00:15:13.998
- Is he sad?
- I think. Or something.

132
00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:20.546
Good night, honey.

133
00:15:22.631 --> 00:15:25.259
Can you get me some floss in the morning?

134
00:15:25.342 --> 00:15:27.303
- Floss?
- Yeah, the strawberry kind.

135
00:15:27.386 --> 00:15:29.221
Sure.

136
00:15:32.266 --> 00:15:34.351
Good night, Bear.

137
00:15:35.394 --> 00:15:37.479
Creasy Bear.

138
00:16:10.804 --> 00:16:15.309
- What's that one for?
- La Virgen de Guadalupe.

139
00:16:15.392 --> 00:16:19.229
Business. For Toyota, for Ford.

140
00:16:19.313 --> 00:16:24.818
If one dies, maybe she can
resurrect the other one. I don't know.

141
00:16:27.112 --> 00:16:29.198
She likes him.

142
00:16:30.157 --> 00:16:33.202
- What are you talkin' about?
- Creasy.

143
00:16:34.703 --> 00:16:36.789
Pita likes him.

144
00:16:38.290 --> 00:16:44.672
Pita loves school. Pita would love Count
Dracula if he took her back there, honey.

145
00:16:44.755 --> 00:16:46.632
OK?

146
00:16:48.509 --> 00:16:51.220
Hey. Are you OK?

147
00:16:51.303 --> 00:16:53.764
- I don't know.
- OK?

148
00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:59.770
I don't know, Lisa. I'm trying.

149
00:17:56.076 --> 00:17:57.953
Come on, Bird.

150
00:17:58.036 --> 00:18:00.998
That's right, that's right. Come on.

151
00:18:01.081 --> 00:18:02.833
All right.

152
00:18:02.916 --> 00:18:04.835
Home to Emilio.

153
00:18:05.794 --> 00:18:07.796
You're home free, baby.

154
00:18:27.858 --> 00:18:30.652
- Where are you from, Creasy?
- The US.

155
00:18:30.736 --> 00:18:33.697
- I know, but which state?
- No state in particular.

156
00:18:33.781 --> 00:18:41.455
- You can drive and talk at the same time.
- No, I can't, Pita, so please let me do my job.

157
00:18:41.538 --> 00:18:43.248
Are you going to stay?

158
00:18:44.666 --> 00:18:49.505
My last bodyguard left. Somebody
gave him more money than we could.

159
00:18:49.588 --> 00:18:53.550
I guess that makes me a bargain then, huh?

160
00:18:53.634 --> 00:18:58.806
Being black. Is that a positive or a negative
for a bodyguard in Mexico?

161
00:18:58.889 --> 00:19:01.099
Time will tell.

162
00:19:03.644 --> 00:19:07.773
There were 24 kidnappings in Mexico City
in the last six days.

163
00:19:07.856 --> 00:19:10.442
- Four a day.
- Yeah? 24?

164
00:19:10.526 --> 00:19:14.321
- 24. What do you think about that?
- I think you know more than you should.

165
00:19:14.404 --> 00:19:16.240
Well, thank you.

166
00:19:44.476 --> 00:19:47.312
- See you later.
- You have to sign.

167
00:19:47.396 --> 00:19:50.774
- What?
- You have to sign in. Show them your ID.

168
00:19:53.026 --> 00:19:54.361
Come on.

169
00:19:55.612 --> 00:19:57.364
Right there.

170
00:20:13.297 --> 00:20:16.717
Pita! It's so good to have you back.

171
00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:20.137
Sister Anna,
this is my new bodyguard, Creasy.

172
00:20:20.220 --> 00:20:24.308
- Sister Anna, the headmistress.
- Señor Creasy.

173
00:20:25.559 --> 00:20:29.938
- Hurry. Class is about to begin. Go, go.
- Bye, Creasy.

174
00:20:31.231 --> 00:20:34.818
You must look after our Pita.
It is not good that she is late today.

175
00:20:34.902 --> 00:20:39.364
I'm very sorry. I have to get used to
the routes. It won't happen again.

176
00:20:39.448 --> 00:20:43.201
No offence, but I regret that
your profession needs to exist.

177
00:20:43.285 --> 00:20:46.371
So do I, Madre, so do I.

178
00:20:46.455 --> 00:20:50.208
Do you ever see the hand of God
in what you do?

179
00:20:51.877 --> 00:20:53.962
No, not for a long time.

180
00:20:54.046 --> 00:20:56.924
The Bible says,
be not overcome of evil...

181
00:20:57.007 --> 00:21:01.219
But overcome evil with good.

182
00:21:01.303 --> 00:21:04.181
That's Romans Chapter 12 Verse 21.

183
00:21:07.142 --> 00:21:10.187
I am the sheep that got lost, Madre.

184
00:22:13.542 --> 00:22:17.921
When you were a kid, Creasy,
did you like school?

185
00:22:18.005 --> 00:22:20.382
- I don't remember.
- You don't remember?

186
00:22:20.465 --> 00:22:24.386
No, I don't remember.
No, I didn't like it.

187
00:22:24.469 --> 00:22:26.763
Why not?

188
00:22:26.847 --> 00:22:31.351
Because it wasn't a school like yours, Pita.
There was no Sister Anna.

189
00:22:34.021 --> 00:22:36.398
Were you unhappy?

190
00:22:38.525 --> 00:22:41.987
Being unhappy, that's a state of mind.
I really don't remember.

191
00:22:51.371 --> 00:22:53.749
What happened to your hand?

192
00:22:55.125 --> 00:22:56.918
- It's a birth defect.
- No, it's not.

193
00:22:57.002 --> 00:22:58.503
Look, no more questions, OK?

194
00:23:01.381 --> 00:23:05.260
- It really wasn't a question.
- It sounded like a question to me.

195
00:23:08.889 --> 00:23:11.266
Listen to me.
I'm being paid to protect you.

196
00:23:11.349 --> 00:23:12.392
No, no, no.

197
00:23:12.476 --> 00:23:16.021
I'm being paid to be your bodyguard.
Look at me.

198
00:23:16.563 --> 00:23:22.903
I'm not being paid to be your friend, but
to protect you. So no more questions, period.

199
00:23:24.863 --> 00:23:26.448
- Do you hear me?
- Yes.

200
00:23:29.242 --> 00:23:31.870
- No crying.
- I'm not crying.

201
00:23:32.913 --> 00:23:35.040
Well, don't start.

202
00:23:35.123 --> 00:23:38.627
You gotta understand, this is a job.
In order for me to do my job...

203
00:23:41.296 --> 00:23:43.590
Wait a minute.

204
00:24:31.888 --> 00:24:33.974
Yeah, come in.

205
00:24:39.563 --> 00:24:41.648
Mr Creasy.

206
00:24:42.357 --> 00:24:45.318
I just wanted to make sure
you have everything you need.

207
00:24:45.402 --> 00:24:46.862
I'm fine, thanks.

208
00:24:48.488 --> 00:24:52.993
Is the food all right?
Because Maria told me you didn't eat.

209
00:24:54.578 --> 00:24:59.332
Yeah, the food is great.
I just wasn't that hungry tonight.

210
00:25:01.793 --> 00:25:04.462
So you read the Bible?

211
00:25:05.297 --> 00:25:08.049
Yeah, sometimes.

212
00:25:08.133 --> 00:25:10.260
Does it help?

213
00:25:10.343 --> 00:25:12.053
Yeah, sometimes.

214
00:25:14.306 --> 00:25:17.517
- Can I talk to you for a minute?
- Sure.

215
00:25:19.519 --> 00:25:22.480
How are you doing with Pita?

216
00:25:22.564 --> 00:25:24.149
Fine.

217
00:25:24.232 --> 00:25:27.777
As soon as she figures out that
I'm not her new toy, it'll be fine.

218
00:25:27.861 --> 00:25:30.363
- She told me about that.
- OK.

219
00:25:31.907 --> 00:25:35.285
- You don't have children, do you?
- I told you I didn't.

220
00:25:35.368 --> 00:25:38.330
Well, they can be tenacious
when they want something.

221
00:25:38.413 --> 00:25:41.041
And Pita just wants to be friends.

222
00:25:41.124 --> 00:25:42.792
OK.

223
00:25:42.876 --> 00:25:48.381
But you're paying me to protect her,
not to be her friend, right?

224
00:25:49.883 --> 00:25:51.968
So...

225
00:25:53.261 --> 00:25:55.764
Look, maybe this isn't gonna work out.

226
00:25:55.847 --> 00:26:01.061
Maybe your husband should find
somebody that's a little more sociable.

227
00:26:03.438 --> 00:26:04.814
No, you're right.

228
00:26:07.359 --> 00:26:10.111
You're being paid to protect her.

229
00:26:10.195 --> 00:26:13.740
And I'm confident that you'll do that.

230
00:26:18.203 --> 00:26:23.208
I'll be coming with you tomorrow.
I hope that's all right.

231
00:26:52.279 --> 00:26:55.532
You think God'll forgive us
for what we've done?

232
00:27:21.182 --> 00:27:25.145
I'm tired of killin', Ray.
I'm tired of killin', Ray.

233
00:27:28.106 --> 00:27:32.569
You think God'll forgive us
for what we've done?

234
00:27:32.652 --> 00:27:34.863
In my state, I couldn't...

235
00:27:34.946 --> 00:27:37.073
I couldn't guard a corpse.

236
00:27:37.157 --> 00:27:39.159
They talk all the time.

237
00:27:39.242 --> 00:27:42.078
You know I'm no good at that.

238
00:27:42.454 --> 00:27:45.290
You know I'm no good at that.

239
00:27:46.499 --> 00:27:48.335
You know how they say...

240
00:27:50.128 --> 00:27:53.131
a bullet always tells the truth?

241
00:28:34.339 --> 00:28:36.132
Yeah?

242
00:28:36.216 --> 00:28:38.468
- Hey.
- Crease.

243
00:28:38.551 --> 00:28:40.220
What's wrong?

244
00:28:40.303 --> 00:28:46.393
Hey, listen, you ever have
a 9mm round that didn't go off?

245
00:28:46.476 --> 00:28:49.104
Yeah. Failure to fire.

246
00:28:49.187 --> 00:28:52.357
I know, failure to fire and...

247
00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:57.487
You know, I pulled the trigger
and click, nothing.

248
00:28:57.570 --> 00:29:02.033
- You're talkin' about a bad primer.
- Yeah, yeah, but I...

249
00:29:02.117 --> 00:29:06.871
Yeah, right. Dimple on the primer.
That may be...

250
00:29:06.955 --> 00:29:09.332
Well, like we used to say...

251
00:29:10.667 --> 00:29:13.461
a bullet always tells the truth.

252
00:29:20.552 --> 00:29:23.430
Crease? You all right?

253
00:29:23.513 --> 00:29:25.265
Yeah.

254
00:29:26.307 --> 00:29:28.726
What were you shootin' at?

255
00:29:28.810 --> 00:29:31.104
Yeah, I'm sorry, Ray.
I'm sorry I woke you.

256
00:29:31.187 --> 00:29:35.233
No, it's OK, it's nothin'.
I was watchin' TV.

257
00:29:37.110 --> 00:29:39.195
OK.

258
00:30:58.816 --> 00:31:01.444
Pita, you have a pencil?

259
00:31:05.907 --> 00:31:07.575
Thank you.

260
00:31:41.276 --> 00:31:46.197
- It's hard to get used to the traffic down here.
- Yeah. I'm very sorry.

261
00:32:06.843 --> 00:32:08.970
- See you, baby.
- See you later.

262
00:32:09.053 --> 00:32:13.391
- Hey, don't forget your towel.
- Thank you.

263
00:32:18.896 --> 00:32:20.773
Bye.

264
00:33:26.422 --> 00:33:29.384
- You're a strong swimmer.
- I never win.

265
00:33:35.306 --> 00:33:37.183
Thanks.

266
00:33:40.478 --> 00:33:43.189
So, what do I do?

267
00:33:43.272 --> 00:33:46.776
You're the fastest in the water,
the slowest off the blocks.

268
00:33:46.859 --> 00:33:49.237
What do you think that means?
What you gotta do?

269
00:33:49.320 --> 00:33:52.448
- Get faster off the blocks?
- Get faster off the blocks.

270
00:33:53.449 --> 00:33:55.868
- Our big swim meet is in three weeks.
- Yeah?

271
00:33:55.952 --> 00:34:01.708
- I was gonna enter the 150 freestyle.
- You'll be fine. You'll be OK.

272
00:34:03.418 --> 00:34:05.795
- I'll still be slow.
- You're not slow.

273
00:34:05.878 --> 00:34:11.092
- I never finish better than third.
- Then maybe you are slow.

274
00:34:13.761 --> 00:34:17.056
With us this evening we have
Mariana Guerrero from Reforma newspaper

275
00:34:17.140 --> 00:34:19.517
to speak with us about the kidnappings.

276
00:34:20.643 --> 00:34:23.896
Who are the ones responsible
for the kidnappings in Mexico?

277
00:34:23.980 --> 00:34:27.734
It is an activity of organised crime.
It's not a random kidnapping.

278
00:34:27.817 --> 00:34:30.027
They are not political kidnappings
like in Colombia.

279
00:34:40.246 --> 00:34:42.957
How do you think he got out?

280
00:34:44.584 --> 00:34:45.960
I let him go.

281
00:34:46.043 --> 00:34:49.714
- It's better to be free, right?
- It's better for him.

282
00:34:51.424 --> 00:34:54.385
Actually, he was driving me crazy.

283
00:34:57.972 --> 00:34:59.891
Good night.

284
00:35:05.021 --> 00:35:06.856
Good night.

285
00:35:22.079 --> 00:35:24.999
- See you in a couple of days, OK? I love you.
- Love you.

286
00:35:25.082 --> 00:35:26.959
Be good. Come on, Lise.

287
00:35:27.043 --> 00:35:30.546
All right, sweetheart,
so we'll call you from Detroit, OK?

288
00:35:31.380 --> 00:35:33.549
- I love you.
- Love you.

289
00:35:37.929 --> 00:35:42.308
- OK, bye, honey. I love you!
- Love you.

290
00:35:47.355 --> 00:35:49.190
I hate leaving her.

291
00:36:02.745 --> 00:36:04.997
Concentrating?

292
00:36:05.081 --> 00:36:07.166
Eyes are closed?

293
00:36:11.420 --> 00:36:13.214
- What happened?
- I flinched.

294
00:36:13.297 --> 00:36:15.716
The gunshot holds no fear. Say it.

295
00:36:15.800 --> 00:36:19.220
- The gunshot holds no fear.
- The gunshot holds no fear! Say it!

296
00:36:19.303 --> 00:36:21.013
- The gunshot holds no fear.
- Louder!

297
00:36:21.097 --> 00:36:23.349
- The gunshot holds no fear!
- Louder!

298
00:36:23.432 --> 00:36:27.061
- The gunshot holds no fear!
- That's good. You welcome the sound.

299
00:36:27.144 --> 00:36:29.272
In fact, it's the sound that sets you free.

300
00:36:29.355 --> 00:36:33.734
You are a prisoner on this block until
that sound sets you free. Are you ready?

301
00:36:33.818 --> 00:36:36.529
- Yes.
- Are you ready? Are you set?

302
00:36:44.579 --> 00:36:46.664
Creasy?

303
00:36:46.747 --> 00:36:49.083
What's a concubine?

304
00:36:49.166 --> 00:36:52.461
- Why do you ask?
- It's in my history book.

305
00:36:53.504 --> 00:36:57.300
- It's like a wife, right?
- Yeah, yeah, it's...

306
00:36:57.383 --> 00:36:59.760
Can I see that? It's kind of a wife.

307
00:36:59.844 --> 00:37:01.220
Right there.

308
00:37:01.304 --> 00:37:04.599
But the Emperor of China had 1,000 of them.

309
00:37:06.392 --> 00:37:10.354
OK, like nowadays, in the West,
they have one husband for one wife.

310
00:37:10.438 --> 00:37:17.194
But in the olden-time cultures they had,
you know, different... different rules.

311
00:37:18.988 --> 00:37:21.073
Why? You feel sorry for the husband?

312
00:37:21.157 --> 00:37:25.411
Yeah. Can you imagine my mom
multiplied by a thousand?

313
00:37:26.913 --> 00:37:29.373
Creasy.

314
00:37:29.457 --> 00:37:32.084
- You're smiling.
- What?

315
00:37:32.168 --> 00:37:34.420
- You were smiling.
- No, I'm not.

316
00:37:34.503 --> 00:37:35.755
- You were.
- No, I was not.

317
00:37:35.838 --> 00:37:38.591
- You're not now, but you were.
- You were smiling. I wasn't.

318
00:37:38.674 --> 00:37:40.092
- You were.
- When?

319
00:37:40.176 --> 00:37:42.720
- Five seconds ago.
- I'm not smiling.

320
00:37:42.803 --> 00:37:47.516
- Well, a second ago you were.
- You said five seconds ago. Now that's six.

321
00:37:47.600 --> 00:37:49.810
- Ten seconds ago.
- Ten seconds ago I was smiling.

322
00:37:49.894 --> 00:37:53.981
OK, in the next ten seconds,
we'll see who smiles first.

323
00:37:57.443 --> 00:37:59.946
- You smiled already. See? You did.
- You.

324
00:38:00.029 --> 00:38:02.531
No, that wasn't a... That was a smirk.

325
00:38:02.615 --> 00:38:08.329
That's not a smile. A smirk is different. They
both start with S, but they're not the same...

326
00:38:08.412 --> 00:38:11.207
- Do your homework.
- You were.

327
00:38:14.251 --> 00:38:16.128
Bang!

328
00:38:17.088 --> 00:38:19.757
Stop, stop, stop.
Come back, come back.

329
00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:21.133
Bang!

330
00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:24.679
Stop, stop, stop, stop, stop, stop.

331
00:38:24.762 --> 00:38:28.182
Come here. Hurry up, hurry up.

332
00:38:28.265 --> 00:38:29.934
Set.

333
00:38:30.017 --> 00:38:32.520
Bang! Bang!

334
00:38:35.690 --> 00:38:40.069
You don't flinch when you hear
the gunshot, understand?

335
00:38:40.152 --> 00:38:45.366
Listen for the sound. You don't anticipate.
Concentrate on the sound. Understand me?

336
00:38:45.449 --> 00:38:47.535
They're gaining on you. Go, go, go, go!

337
00:38:47.618 --> 00:38:51.998
Stop, stop! Come on, get out. Let's go again.

338
00:39:11.350 --> 00:39:12.852
- Daddy!
- Come here, girl.

339
00:39:14.353 --> 00:39:17.481
- I missed you so much.
- I missed you.

340
00:39:17.565 --> 00:39:20.776
I got a surprise for you. Are you ready?

341
00:39:21.318 --> 00:39:23.404
You got me a dog! You got me a dog!

342
00:39:24.071 --> 00:39:26.991
- You bought me a dog! Oh, my gosh!
- What do you think?

343
00:39:27.074 --> 00:39:30.578
Oh, my gosh.
Just what I wanted. What's his name?

344
00:39:30.661 --> 00:39:33.664
- Sam. Like Dad.
- Come on, Sam! Come on, Sam!

345
00:39:35.291 --> 00:39:37.376
State...

346
00:39:39.837 --> 00:39:42.715
Bhutan. It's a Himalayan kingdom.

347
00:39:42.798 --> 00:39:46.385
They were having some problems
with the royal family not long ago.

348
00:39:46.469 --> 00:39:48.179
OK.

349
00:39:50.056 --> 00:39:52.516
Any more questions?

350
00:39:52.600 --> 00:39:57.897
- Do you have a girlfriend, Creasy?
- What? No. What kind of question is that?

351
00:39:57.980 --> 00:40:01.275
- You're supposed to be studying history.
- It's Creasy history.

352
00:40:01.358 --> 00:40:04.278
- No, ancient history.
- Who was your very first girlfriend?

353
00:40:04.361 --> 00:40:05.488
- Nonya.
- Nonya?

354
00:40:05.571 --> 00:40:09.033
Nonya business, that's who. OK?

355
00:40:09.742 --> 00:40:11.702
Hi.

356
00:40:11.786 --> 00:40:15.498
Tomorrow after you drop off Pita,
could you take me to get my hair done?

357
00:40:15.581 --> 00:40:17.666
Yes, ma'am.

358
00:40:17.750 --> 00:40:20.753
All right. Well, I'll...

359
00:40:20.836 --> 00:40:23.547
I'll leave you to your history.

360
00:40:23.631 --> 00:40:26.550
- Good night.
- Good night, honey.

361
00:40:29.345 --> 00:40:31.472
- OK, now ask me.
- Ask you what?

362
00:40:37.853 --> 00:40:40.940
Go, Pita! Go, go, go, go, go!

363
00:40:43.109 --> 00:40:45.611
Go, go, go, go, go!

364
00:40:49.323 --> 00:40:51.575
- 10.99.
- Yes!

365
00:40:54.870 --> 00:40:57.456
- I'm tough, Creasy.
- No such thing as tough.

366
00:40:57.540 --> 00:41:00.918
There's trained and there's untrained.
Now, which are you?

367
00:41:01.001 --> 00:41:04.463
- Trained.
- Trained. OK, we'll go again.

368
00:41:12.805 --> 00:41:14.890
- Here.
- Stand here near the finish line.

369
00:41:14.974 --> 00:41:16.600
OK. Hey.

370
00:41:16.684 --> 00:41:19.895
I'm a prisoner in the block
until the gunshot sets me free.

371
00:41:19.979 --> 00:41:23.899
That's right. Don't smile, don't fool around
if you wanna win. Trained or untrained?

372
00:41:23.983 --> 00:41:25.651
- Trained.
- Go.

373
00:41:26.694 --> 00:41:31.407
- Señor Creasy, nice to see you.
- Good to see you, Madre.

374
00:41:31.490 --> 00:41:34.160
Pita's parents are away
on business in Juárez.

375
00:41:34.243 --> 00:41:36.912
Today, you are her father.

376
00:43:07.920 --> 00:43:11.090
I won, Creasy! I won!

377
00:43:11.173 --> 00:43:13.676
- OK.
- I won!

378
00:43:23.978 --> 00:43:28.482
- Once upon a time, when we were young...
- When I was young.

379
00:43:28.565 --> 00:43:31.568
Well, when we were young
and he was younger,

380
00:43:31.652 --> 00:43:34.530
and all heads turned our way,

381
00:43:34.613 --> 00:43:37.241
we made a deal to take the world together.

382
00:43:37.324 --> 00:43:41.287
Yeah, then one day I got a call,
and you said...

383
00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:44.790
I'm in love, I'm in love!

384
00:43:44.873 --> 00:43:47.334
And I'm movin' to Mexico!

385
00:43:47.418 --> 00:43:49.962
And I said...

386
00:43:50.045 --> 00:43:53.590
I said, what happened to the plan?
What happened to it?

387
00:43:53.674 --> 00:43:58.512
- I said, the plan's right here!
- Yeah, yeah. And what'd I do?

388
00:43:58.595 --> 00:44:00.931
I hung up. And then I met Alicia.

389
00:44:01.015 --> 00:44:05.311
And then I went, now I got ya. I got ya.

390
00:44:05.394 --> 00:44:08.188
I got it. Can I kiss her?

391
00:44:08.272 --> 00:44:10.274
Absolutely.

392
00:44:10.357 --> 00:44:13.110
Hey, what are you doin'?

393
00:44:17.573 --> 00:44:22.286
- You got me.
- OK, I think now's as good a time as any.

394
00:44:25.122 --> 00:44:27.875
I bought it with my own money.

395
00:44:29.793 --> 00:44:31.879
Thank you.

396
00:44:33.464 --> 00:44:35.549
Open it.

397
00:44:39.887 --> 00:44:44.475
It's Saint Jude,
the patron saint of lost causes.

398
00:44:48.270 --> 00:44:50.272
Well deserved.

399
00:44:54.318 --> 00:44:57.112
Thank you, Pita. It's beautiful.

400
00:44:58.572 --> 00:45:00.657
You're welcome.

401
00:45:49.998 --> 00:45:52.042
- Dad?
- Yes, sweetie?

402
00:45:52.126 --> 00:45:54.711
- Can I talk to you?
- Yes.

403
00:45:56.338 --> 00:45:59.383
I don't wanna play piano, I wanna swim.

404
00:45:59.466 --> 00:46:03.804
It's not open for discussion, honey, OK?
Mr Lozzi's a very, very famous teacher.

405
00:46:03.887 --> 00:46:08.225
If he accepts you as a student,
you're gonna play the piano. Sorry.

406
00:46:08.308 --> 00:46:10.269
- Whatever.
- Baby.

407
00:46:12.813 --> 00:46:15.441
- I love you.
- Love you.

408
00:46:15.524 --> 00:46:18.777
- I just want what's best for you, you know?
- OK.

409
00:46:18.861 --> 00:46:21.113
OK, honey.

410
00:46:31.290 --> 00:46:34.084
If you broke all my fingers,
then taped them back together,

411
00:46:34.168 --> 00:46:37.045
I wouldn't be able to play piano,
but I could still swim.

412
00:46:37.129 --> 00:46:39.423
Sam, get back.

413
00:46:39.506 --> 00:46:42.509
Don't be a crybaby.
You're tougher than that.

414
00:46:42.593 --> 00:46:44.678
Sit, sit, sit, sit, sit, sit.

415
00:46:47.931 --> 00:46:50.476
Remember the day you wanted the pencil?

416
00:46:50.559 --> 00:46:53.729
- Yeah.
- I know why.

417
00:46:53.812 --> 00:46:55.355
Yeah?

418
00:46:55.439 --> 00:47:00.110
You wanted the licence number off of that car.
I wrote it down in my notebook.

419
00:47:00.194 --> 00:47:02.863
I got it all but the last number.

420
00:47:02.946 --> 00:47:06.200
I'll get it from you later. Can you belch?

421
00:47:06.283 --> 00:47:08.535
Like burp. Can you burp?

422
00:47:12.789 --> 00:47:17.419
- That's good. That's very good.
- I just had a Coke.

423
00:47:17.503 --> 00:47:19.880
Listen to me. This famous teacher...

424
00:47:19.963 --> 00:47:24.051
He teaches a lot of rich kids and plays
for the symphonies and all that, right?

425
00:47:24.134 --> 00:47:26.803
Belch every few minutes
while you're practising.

426
00:47:26.887 --> 00:47:31.725
You apologise to him, but you keep belching.
You'll offend every sensibility he has.

427
00:47:31.808 --> 00:47:35.521
Very good. You'll be back in the pool
in 24 hours, I guarantee you.

428
00:47:35.604 --> 00:47:37.689
Right, Sam?

429
00:47:44.112 --> 00:47:46.823
Lupita Ramos.

430
00:47:49.993 --> 00:47:52.162
For you, Creasy.

431
00:47:55.415 --> 00:47:57.292
Thank you.

432
00:48:00.587 --> 00:48:03.924
- How does this look?
- Good. Good.

433
00:48:08.679 --> 00:48:09.346
Come on in.

434
00:48:09.429 --> 00:48:10.472
Bye.

435
00:48:10.556 --> 00:48:12.641
- How long?
- One hour.

436
00:50:18.266 --> 00:50:19.351
Pita!

437
00:50:22.104 --> 00:50:22.979
Pita!

438
00:50:33.073 --> 00:50:35.117
Pita!

439
00:50:44.084 --> 00:50:45.752
Run!

440
00:52:04.456 --> 00:52:06.917
Creasy!

441
00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.002
Creasy!

442
00:52:11.129 --> 00:52:13.381
Creasy. Creasy!

443
00:52:14.257 --> 00:52:16.384
Creasy!

444
00:52:28.772 --> 00:52:30.315
I can't...

445
00:52:53.421 --> 00:52:58.134
John W Creasy is under arrest for the murder
of two officers of the Judicial Police.

446
00:52:58.218 --> 00:52:59.511
Creasy!

447
00:53:09.521 --> 00:53:13.191
This man, John W Creasy,

448
00:53:13.275 --> 00:53:14.901
an American citizen,

449
00:53:14.985 --> 00:53:16.778
is under arrest for the murder

450
00:53:17.028 --> 00:53:19.489
of two officers of the Judicial Police

451
00:53:22.158 --> 00:53:24.828
and is suspected of possible involvement

452
00:53:24.911 --> 00:53:27.664
in the kidnapping of Lupita Martin Ramos.

453
00:53:29.833 --> 00:53:32.502
Chief Ramirez...

454
00:53:34.671 --> 00:53:37.215
The two officers who were killed.

455
00:53:37.299 --> 00:53:39.676
Records show they were off duty at the time.

456
00:53:40.385 --> 00:53:42.888
So why were they in uniform

457
00:53:43.179 --> 00:53:44.139
and in a patrol car?

458
00:53:44.222 --> 00:53:47.976
All I know is that they died bravely.

459
00:53:48.935 --> 00:53:50.186
Of course,

460
00:53:50.270 --> 00:53:52.981
but what exactly were they doing

461
00:53:53.064 --> 00:53:54.482
at the scene of the kidnapping?

462
00:53:55.191 --> 00:53:58.320
Or were they known
for their exceptional good luck?

463
00:53:58.403 --> 00:54:00.405
They were known for being corrupt

464
00:54:00.488 --> 00:54:02.949
and now are celebrated for being dead.

465
00:54:59.923 --> 00:55:02.384
Excuse me.

466
00:55:08.098 --> 00:55:10.266
Relax, OK? Relax, Sammy.

467
00:55:15.730 --> 00:55:19.234
I know she's your little girl. When
I tell you everything's gonna be all right,

468
00:55:19.317 --> 00:55:21.987
everything's gonna be all right.

469
00:55:23.655 --> 00:55:26.032
Señor Ramos.

470
00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:36.626
I'm sorry. I'm really sorry.

471
00:55:36.710 --> 00:55:40.505
Victor Fuentes, Anti-Kidnapping Division,
Policía Judicial.

472
00:55:40.588 --> 00:55:44.217
Excuse me. I'm Jordan Kalfus.
I'm the family attorney.

473
00:55:44.300 --> 00:55:49.681
Speak slower, please.
My Russian is better than my English.

474
00:55:49.764 --> 00:55:54.602
Well, I'm conducting the negotiations, and we
neither need nor want any police assistance.

475
00:55:54.686 --> 00:55:58.398
We're gonna handle this thing ourselves.

476
00:55:59.149 --> 00:56:05.655
Señor Ramos, two police officers were killed
during your daughter's abduction.

477
00:56:05.739 --> 00:56:08.658
I have a written order from...

478
00:56:08.825 --> 00:56:10.785
the Public Minister...

479
00:56:11.036 --> 00:56:13.038
authorising our participation...

480
00:56:13.121 --> 00:56:15.749
unofficially.

481
00:56:16.791 --> 00:56:21.588
If you want to speak to
Attorney General Diaz, it's on me.

482
00:56:23.715 --> 00:56:25.425
OK.

483
00:56:25.508 --> 00:56:29.929
The kidnapper will tell you
to deliver the money alone.

484
00:56:30.638 --> 00:56:32.599
Por favor, don't do that.

